  "slug": "mamma-mia-meets-the-strangers-its-a-movie-swap",
  "title": "'Mamma Mia!' Meets 'The Strangers'! It's a Movie Swap!",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Amanda Dobbins"
  ],
  "published": "2026-02-06",
  "runtimeMin": 99,
  "format": "The sixth Sean-and-Amanda movie swap: she watches 'The Strangers,' he finally watches 'Mamma Mia!,' both from 2008, and they argue about not knowing.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "'The Strangers'",
      "note": "Sean's pick — Amanda watches for the first time",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The Strangers",
          "year": 2008,
          "note": "Brian Bertino's directorial debut, shot in 2006-07 and shelved a year. Liv Tyler and Scott Speedman come home from a wedding where his proposal was turned down; three masked strangers terrorize them for no reason. Both love that it withholds almost everything: the killers stay masked, and the only explanation ('Because you were home') is the one moment Sean thinks tips too far. Made $85M; Amanda gives it 3.5 stars on Letterboxd."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "'Mamma Mia!'",
      "note": "Amanda's pick — Sean finally watches it",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Mamma Mia!",
          "year": 2008,
          "note": "Phyllida Lloyd's only feature (before The Iron Lady), an ABBA jukebox musical shot in Greece. Sean calls it simultaneously very good and very badly directed, like great karaoke with famous people slightly hungover on vacation. Amanda's peak: Meryl Streep singing 'The Winner Takes It All' at Pierce Brosnan on a cliff. Made $610M worldwide; third-highest-grossing movie musical if you drop the Disney titles. Ends without naming the father, the swap's shared theme of not knowing."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
